# Class Data Library Milestone #2

### General requirements:

* You need to follow the style laid out in the [C# Coding Conventions](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/programming-guide/inside-a-program/coding-conventions)

* Document your code from Assignment #1 using [XML comments](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/codedoc)

* Write tests for code coverage

### Assignment requirements:

* Refactor any code that needs corrected from Milestone #1

* Add XML comments to your code from Milestone #1

* Pull the test project from upstream into your project

* Write the body of all test methods supplied in the test project

* Add a new test class for `WarriorWater`, and write test methods similar to those found in the other drink classes testing the expected functionality of the `WarriorWater`.

* When all tests are written your code should have a minimum code coverage of 92%

### Purpose:

This assignment is designed for an introduction to testing. In a professional environment you will be required to write tests for the code you write. In my experience (this is Zachery Brunner) companies normally require 80-85% of all application code to be tested before allowing the project to be put into production. You will be expected to be able to write tests this semester so please ensure you understand this assignment and do not just go through the motions of doing it.

```csharp
/*

* Purpose: Provide an example of tests the students will encounter within Data Library Milestone #2

/*
* Enum for Size of a milkshake
*/
public enum Size
{
    Short,
    Tall,
    Venti,
}

/*
* Enum for Flavor of a milkshake
*/
public enum Flavor
{
    Vanilla,
    Chocolate,
    Mint
}

/*
* Class for the milkshake
*/
public class Milkshake
{
    /* Private variable declaration for the milkshake */
    private bool toppings = false;
    private bool whippedCream = true;
    private bool cherry = true;
    private Size size = Size.Short;
    private Flavor iceCreamFlavor = Flavor.Vanilla;

    public bool Toppings
    {
        get { return toppings; }
        set { toppings = value; }
    }

    public bool WhippedCream
    {
        get { return whippedCream; }
        set { whippedCream = value; }
    }

    public bool Cherry
    {
        get { return cherry; }
        set { cherry = value; }
    }

    public Size Size
    {
        get { return size; }
        set { size = value; }
    }

    public Flavor IceCreamFlavor
    {
        get { return iceCreamFlavor; }
        set { iceCreamFlavor = value; }
    }

    public uint Calories
    {
        get
        {
            switch(size)
            {
                case Size.Short: return 100;
                case Size.Tall: return 200;
                case Size.Venti: return 300;
                default: throw new NotImplementedException($"Unknown size {Size}");
            }
        }
    }

    public double Price
    {
        get
        {
            switch(Size)
            {
                case Size.Short: return 2.50;
                case Size.Tall: return 3.75;
                case Size.Venti: return 5.00;
                default: throw new NotImplementedException($"Unknown size {Size}");
            }
        }
    }

    public List<string> SpecialInstructions
    {
        get
        {
            List<string> instructions = new List<string>();
            if(Toppings) instructions.Add("Add toppings");
            if(!WhippedCream) instructions.Add("Hold whipped cream");
            if(!Cherry) instructions.Add("Hold cherry");
            return instructions;
        }
    }

    public override string ToString()
    {
        return $"{Size} {IceCreamFlavor} Milkshake";
    }
}
```

First, let's add XML comments for the above classes and enumerations.  These should be included for all Class, Enum, and Struct definitions, as well as all methods:

```csharp
/*
* Author: Zachery Brunner
* Purpose: Provide an example of tests the students will encounter within Data Library Milestone #2
*/

/// <summary>
/// Enum for Size of a milkshake
/// </summary>
public enum Size
{
    Short,
    Tall,
    Venti,
}

/// <summary>
/// Enum for Flavor of a milkshake
/// </summary>
public enum Flavor
{
    Vanilla,
    Chocolate,
    Mint
}

/// <summary>
/// Class for representing a milkshake 
/// </summary>
public class Milkshake
{
    /* Private variable declaration for the milkshake */
    private bool toppings = false;
    private bool whippedCream = true;
    private bool cherry = true;
    private Size size = Size.Short;
    private Flavor iceCreamFlavor = Flavor.Vanilla;

    /// <summary>
    /// If this mikshake is served with toppings 
    /// </summary>
    public bool Toppings
    {
        get { return toppings; }
        set { toppings = value; }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// If this milkshake is served with whipped cream
    /// </summary>
    public bool WhippedCream
    {
        get { return whippedCream; }
        set { whippedCream = value; }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// If this milkshake has a cherry on top 
    /// </summary>
    public bool Cherry
    {
        get { return cherry; }
        set { cherry = value; }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// The size of the milkshake 
    /// </summary>
    public Size Size
    {
        get { return size; }
        set { size = value; }
    }

    /// <summary> 
    /// The flavor of the milkshake 
    /// </summary>
    public Flavor IceCreamFlavor
    {
        get { return iceCreamFlavor; }
        set { iceCreamFlavor = value; }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// The calories of the milkshake 
    /// </summary>
    /// <exception cref="System.NotImplementedException">
    /// Thrown if the calories for the size is not known 
    /// </exception>
    public uint Calories
    {
        get
        {
            switch(size)
            {
                case Size.Short: return 100;
                case Size.Tall: return 200;
                case Size.Venti: return 300;
                default: throw new NotImplementedException($"Unknown size {Size}");
            }
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// The price of the milkshake 
    /// </summary>
    /// <exception cref="System.NotImplementedException">
    /// Thrown if the price for the size is not known 
    /// </exception>
    public double Price
    {
        get
        {
            switch(Size)
            {
                case Size.Short: return 2.50;
                case Size.Tall: return 3.75;
                case Size.Venti: return 5.00;
                default: throw new NotImplementedException($"Unknown size {Size}");
            }
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// A list of special instructions for preparing the milkshake 
    /// </summary>
    public List<string> SpecialInstructions
    {
        get
        {
            List<string> instructions = new List<string>();
            if(Toppings) instructions.Add("Add toppings");
            if(!WhippedCream) instructions.Add("Hold whipped cream");
            if(!Cherry) instructions.Add("Hold cherry");
            return instructions;
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Returns a description of the milkshake 
    /// </summary>
    /// <returns>
    /// A string describing the milkshake 
    /// </returns>
    public override string ToString()
    {
        return $"{Size} {IceCreamFlavor} Milkshake";
    }
}
```

Now let's write some tests for the above class. I will test each element in the order that it appears in the class for easy reference.

```csharp
[Fact]
public void ToppingsShouldBeFalseByDefault()
{
    var MS = new Milkshake();
    Assert.False(MS.Toppings);
}

[Fact]
public void WhippedCreamShouldBeTrueByDefault()
{
    var MS = new Milkshake();
    Assert.True(MS.WhippedCream);
}

[Fact]
public void CherryShouldBeTrueByDefault()
{
    var MS = new Milkshake();
    Assert.True(MS.Cherry);
}

[Fact]
public void MilkshakeShouldBeShortByDefault()
{
    var MS = new Milkshake();
    Assert.Equal(MS.Size, Size.Short);
}

[Fact]
public void MilkshakeShouldBeVanillaByDefault()
{
    var MS = new Milkshake();
    Assert.Equal(MS.IceCreamFlavor, Flavor.Vanilla);
}

[Fact]
public void ShouldBeAbleToSetToppings()
{
    var MS = new Milkshake();
    MS.Toppings = true;
    Assert.True(MS.Toppings);
    MS.Toppings = false;
    Assert.False(MS.Toppings);
}

[Fact]
public void ShouldBeAbleToSetWhippedCream()
{
    var MS = new Milkshake();
    MS.WhippedCream = false;
    Assert.False(MS.WhippedCream);
    MS.WhippedCream = true;
    Assert.True(MS.WhippedCream);
}

[Fact]
public void ShouldBeAbleToSetCherry()
{
    var MS = new Milkshake();
    MS.Cherry = false;
    Assert.False(MS.Cherry);
    MS.Cherry = true;
    Assert.True(MS.Cherry);
}

[Fact]
public void ShouldBeAbleToSetSize()
{
    var MS = new Milkshake();
    MS.Size = Size.Tall;
    Assert.Equal(MS.Size, Size.Tall);
    MS.Size = Size.Venti;
    Assert.Equal(MS.Size, Size.Venti);
    MS.Size = Size.Short;
    Assert.Equal(MS.Size, Size.Short);
}

[Fact]
public void ShouldBeAbleToSetIceCreamFlavor()
{
    var MS = new Milkshake();
    MS.IceCreamFlavor = Flavor.Chocolate;
    Assert.Equal(MS.IceCreamFlavor, Flavor.Chocolate);
    MS.IceCreamFlavor = Flavor.Mint;
    Assert.Equal(MS.IceCreamFlavor, Flavor.Mint);
    MS.IceCreamFlavor = Flavor.Vanilla;
    Assert.Equal(MS.IceCreamFlavor, Flavor.Vanilla);
}

[Theory]
[InlineData(Size.Short, 100)]
[InlineData(Size.Tall, 200)]
[InlineData(Size.Venti, 300)]
public void ShouldHaveCorrectCaloriesForSize(Size size, uint cal)
{
    var MS = new Milkshake()
    {
        Size = size
    };
    Assert.Equal(cal, MS.Calories);
}

[Theory]
[InlineData(Size.Short, 2.50)]
[InlineData(Size.Tall, 3.75)]
[InlineData(Size.Venti, 5.00)]
public void ShouldHaveCorrectPriceForSize(Size size, double price)
{
    var MS = new Milkshake()
    {
        Size = size
    };
    Assert.Equal(price, MS.Price);
}

[Theory]
[InlineData(true, true, true)]
[InlineData(true, true, false)]
[InlineData(true, false, true)]
[InlineData(false, true, true)]
[InlineData(true, false, false)]
[InlineData(false, true, false)]
[InlineData(false, false, true)]
[InlineData(false, false, false)]
public void ShouldHaveCorrectSpecialInstructions(bool includeToppings, bool includeWhippedCream, bool includeCherry)
{
    var MS = new Milkshake()
    {
        Toppings = includeToppings,
        WhippedCream = includeWhippedCream,
        Cherry = includeCherry
    };

    if(includeToppings) Assert.Contains("Add toppings", MS.SpecialInstructions);
 
    if(!includeWhippedCream) Assert.Contains("Hold whipped cream", MS.SpecialInstructions);
 
    if(!includeCherry) Assert.Contains("Hold cherry", MS.SpecialInstructions);

    if(!includeToppings && includeWhippedCream && includeCherry) Assert.Empty(MS.SpecialInstructions);
}

[Theory]
[InlineData(Size.Short, Flavor.Chocolate)]
[InlineData(Size.Short, Flavor.Vanilla)]
[InlineData(Size.Short, Flavor.Mint)]
[InlineData(Size.Tall, Flavor.Chocolate)]
[InlineData(Size.Tall, Flavor.Vanilla)]
[InlineData(Size.Tall, Flavor.Mint)]
[InlineData(Size.Venti, Flavor.Chocolate)]
[InlineData(Size.Venti, Flavor.Vanilla)]
[InlineData(Size.Venti, Flavor.Mint)]
public void ShouldHaveCorrectNameOnToString(Size size, Flavor flavor)
{
    string expectedFlavorName, expectedSizeName;
    
    var MS = new Milkshake()
    {
        Size = size,
        IceCreamFlavor = flavor
    };

    if(size == Size.Short) expectedSizeName = "Short";
    if(size == Size.Tall) expectedSizeName = "Tall";
    if(size == Size.Venti) expectedSizeName = "Venti";

    if(flavor == Flavor.Chocolate) expectedFlavorName = " Chocolate";
    if(flavor == Flavor.Mint) expectedFlavorName = " Mint";
    if(flavor == Flavor.Vanilla) expectedFlavorName = " Vanilla";

    string expectedOutput = expectedSizeName + expectedFlavorName + " Milkshake";

    Assert.Equal(expectedOutput, MS.ToString());
}
```

### Review of what was done above

#### Checking the default values for properties:

* `ToppingsShouldBeFalseByDefault()`

* `WhippedCreamShouldBeTrueByDefault()`

* `CherryShouldBeTrueByDefault()`

* `MilkshakeShouldBeShortByDefault()`

* `MilkshakeShouldBeVanillaByDefault()`

These five test methods are relatively simple. All they test are whether on initialization of the class, the getter returns the expected value.

{{% notice info %}}

Did you know there are two ways common ways to do getter and setters in C#?

If your getter/setter does not need to do anything other than manage a variable, the compiler can create a runtime variable that can not be accessed by using the following line:

```csharp
public bool Cherry { get; set; } = true;
```

However, if you need to be able to access the backing variable or perform logic in a gtter or setter method, you will need to declare a private backing variable:

```csharp
private bool cherry = true;
public bool Cherry
{
    get { return cherry; }
    set { cherry = value; }
}
```
Both of these ways are equivalent in this example
{{% /notice %}}

### Checking the getters/setters

* `ShouldBeAbleToSetToppings()`

* `ShouldBeAbleToSetWhippedCream()`

* `ShouldBeAbleToSetCherry()`

* `ShouldBeAbleToSetSize()`

* `ShouldBeAbleToSetIceCreamFlavor()`

These five tests are a little more complex so lets walk through one of them. Look at `ShouldBeAbleToSetSize()`, in this test we want to test assigning all of the possible sizes to ensure they can be set within the `Size` property. Always create an instance of the class you are testing in the first line of the test. Now, we know that a milkshake’s default size is short, lets iterate through the sizes and ensure they were set correctly. Assign a size of tall and use the Assert.Equal to evaulate the size itself and the size of the milkshake. Rinse and repeat till all possibilities are covered.

```csharp
/* Important Keywords for Testing */

[Fact] /* No if ands or buts about this. There are no possibilities around the given circumstance. It either is or is not */

[Theory] /* The test has different possibilites that need to be checked. This is needed to be able to pass parameters into the functions. Parameters can include what to set variables to or to pass expected values if the return value is based on another parameter. I.E. The price of the milkshake is based on the size of the milkshake */

[InlineData(param1, param2, param3)] /* Accompanied with the [Theory] keyword. The values here must match to the method header parameters. You can have multiple sets of parameters, each set acts like a different test*/

public void TestNameThatTellsYouExactlyWhatTheTestIsTesting(param1, param2, param3) /* The test name should be verbatim what it is testing. If you have a really good method name there is no need for the method comment */
```

Checking variable dependent function

* `ShouldHaveCorrectCaloriesForSize()`

* `ShouldHaveCorrectPriceForSize()`

* `ShouldHaveCorrectSpecialInstructions()`

* `ShouldHaveCorrectNameOnToString()`

Within these four tests the output is completely dependent on current state of the milkshake. Let’s take a closer look at ShouldHaveCorrectPriceForSize(). You can see that there are three different `[InlineData(param1, param2)]` tags. Each corresponding to a different size of milkshake and it’s expected price. The method itself is pretty simple, make a new milkshake and set its size equal to the size parameter and evaulate using an `Assert.Equals()` to see if what we expected the price to be is what the milkshake told us its cost would be.

```csharp
/* Different Assert Statements */

Assert.True(SOMETHING); /* This is stating that property put into the parentheses should evaluate to true */

Assert.False(SOMETHING); /* Same thing as Assert.True just evaluates to false */

Assert.Equal(ExpectedValue, ActualValue); /* Param1(ExpectedValue) should be identical to Param2(ActualValue), probably the most common assert statement you will use. */

Assert.Contains(SomeItem, SomeEnumerable) /* Want to see if a certain phrase or item is within a Enumerable list, use this statement while testing */

Assert.Empty(SomeEnumerable) /* Check to see that a List or other collection is empty */

/* There are more than this but we can go over those as they are needed. For this assignment you should only need those 4 Assert Statements. Interested in learning more? Ask professor Bean or I :) */
```
